A shell grows as the animal adds more material. We can use math to track how the opening of the shell moves as it grows.  We can then change the math to see how the shell might change shape.

Indonesia's baby and mother deaths stay the same.  Even though Indonesia will meet many goals, its health for moms and kids is not good.  Many reasons for this. Indonesia made progress with births helped by a health worker.  Now, 72% have a worker.  But this includes midwives. Midwives cannot help if a birth is hard. Many moms die from bleeding.  Also, less kids go to a health worker for sickness.  Post-birth care is not good either.

C-sections are low, only 4%.  In cities, it is 7%, but in towns, it is 2%.  This means city people have better care.  The poor have less access to care than the rich.  

To help, we need to know if we should focus on programs or the whole health system.  Programs are good because they are easier to do and work fast.  But, they can take money from other health areas.  Also, many programs are not strong.  It makes work harder and costs more.

Victorian books have many details. They show the rich people of that time. Two books from this time, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," are different. They use mystery and strange things that are not usual for books from that time. This makes the characters more interesting. We learn more about why they act the way they do, and how they feel. 

Here is a part from "Oliver Twist": 

"And now, lots of confusing ideas came into his mind. He thought he was still walking with Sikes and Crackit, who were angry and arguing. He could hear their words. But then he realized he was talking to them. Suddenly, he heard gunshots. There were loud yells and lights. He felt like someone was taking him away quickly. All of this was happening so fast. He also felt a pain that would not go away. It hurt him all the time." (Dickens, 220)

Both books use mystery, often in dreams or dreamlike states. In "Oliver Twist," these strange things show us more about Oliver's feelings and thoughts. When Oliver is shot, he remembers it clearly in chapter 28. It is like a dream. He is trying to find help. The part shows how Oliver has no control over what happens. He is very sick. He sees Sikes and Crackit again in his dream. The shooting is scary. Oliver's mind is numb. He does not know who is taking him away. He feels pain all the time. This shows us how much Oliver is suffering.

A few years ago, I worked in an after school program. I helped students in elementary school. I was good at English and reading.  One day, a teacher asked me to help a boy named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade. Adrian had trouble reading. I tried to help him, but it was strange. He read some letters well, but others, not at all. I knew Adrian was Latino. He spoke English well.

We struggled until Adrian's mother came to the program. She only spoke Spanish. I knew a little Spanish, so we talked. Then I understood. Adrian could read, but he did not know the English alphabet well. I am not sure if this helped him much, but I hope he is doing better now.

I tell this story to talk about the language barrier in schools. It is a big problem in California. It is not always easy to see. Even if a child speaks English well, reading can be hard. We all know this problem exists. What can we do?

For Adrian, the answer was simple: tutoring in English reading, especially the alphabet and how to say the letters. But for children who do not speak much English, the answer is harder. There is no one good answer. Dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutors, and ESL classes. None of these things alone will fix the problem. We need to use all of these things together.

First, dual language programs are a good idea. They are good for all children, not just those whose first language is Spanish. Studies show that children in these programs do well in school. Some people are afraid of these programs. They say they waste money and that most children will not benefit. This is not true. If we used these programs more, all children would benefit.

How do we do this? Do we need all teachers to be bilingual? No, that is not reasonable. But we can have bilingual helpers, tutors, or assistants.

When we are small, many of us learn about something big, bigger than we can know. Some go to church, some go to temple, some look inside.  Many take the beliefs of their parents. Some say no to these beliefs. They say there is only what we know, in our own world. We may think one way, then change our minds.  We each try to find our own way to understand the big questions. We look for something to show us the way, to help us.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him what bird he liked best. We sat on our porch. Rain fell on the metal roof. Water ran from the gutters, soaking the plants. He looked out, his eyes searching, remembering. He was thinner now, his clothes loose. His hair was less. He looked out at the rain, not at me. I felt alone, afraid. I did not talk to him about how much I would miss him, because saying it would make it real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer. We watched the rain fall in the June twilight.

My father died in December. Five days after my twenty-second birthday. The medicine did not stop his pain, only made him live longer. I could not say why that was good. What kind of God would do this, I thought. Alone, I did not pray. If God was real, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I did not want to watch him die. So I did not. I wanted to remember him as he lived, not as he died. I knew him better than anyone, better than his family. I knew he would not want me to watch. I stayed in bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one called.

The "Gothic Novel" is strange. It is old and new at the same time.  A writer named Ian Watt said this in a book called "The Rise of the Gothic Novel."  Some people say Gothic stories are not deep. Others say they are great because they make you feel scared and amazed. The first Gothic Novel was "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole. Walpole used old ideas from stories and new ideas from books to make a new kind of story. He used old acting styles and new ways to show nature in his book. He called it "A Gothic Story." The Gothic story uses old ideas from medieval times. It uses old buildings, ideas, and stories. Even when "The Castle of Otranto" was first published, the word "Gothic" meant many things. People thought it meant old and not very good compared to new things. But the Gothic story is a mix of old and new. It uses old ideas and a new way to tell a story. This is why Gothic stories are still popular today. 

One big idea in Gothic stories is chivalry. Chivalry was a way to train knights in the Middle Ages. Gothic writers liked chivalry because it meant bravery, honor, and skill. The writers thought these ideas were missing in their own time. Gothic writers used chivalry to make the past look better and to try to make the present better.  Walpole wrote "The Castle of Otranto" during a time of trouble in politics. He was worried about the future. He may have thought that people in the past were better than people now. This idea is clear in the character Frederic. Frederic is described as:


This description shows many old ideas about knights. Frederic is a prince. He has suffered a lot. He is thought to be dead. He is a brave and polite knight. This is a big part of the Gothic style.

Supply chain management is the way things move from when a customer wants something until it gets to them. This includes getting the materials, making the product, and getting it to the store. A person named Keith Oliver made up the word "supply chain management" in 1982. He said it is about planning, using, and controlling all the parts of the supply chain to make customers happy quickly and well. There are six big parts to a supply chain: making things, getting things, keeping track of things, where things are, moving things, and sharing information. Business leaders use these parts to give good service to customers.

Making things is the first part of the supply chain. It is the base of everything else.  Making things means figuring out when, why, where, and how things will be made. Leaders need to know what people want.  They can look at the market to see what people want.  

The market tells them what people need. Once leaders know what people want, they can decide what to make and how much to make. Then, they need to decide where to make it.  They need to choose a place that can make a lot of good things and keep the quality high. The leaders have to make sure the customers will be happy. After the place is chosen, the next step is to plan how much work each person will do and how to keep the machines working well. Making things is very important. Every detail has to be planned carefully. If one small thing is wrong, it can cost the company a lot of time and money later.

The second big part of the supply chain is getting things. This means making smart choices about how to get the things a company needs. A company might have many different places where things are made. Each place might have different machines, workers, and special skills. The leader has to decide which place is best for each part of the making process. The leader might also choose to get things from other companies. This is called outsourcing. Leaders do this to make things faster and cheaper.

Hitler live in Burma, sign say.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stand alone on street corner.  She hold a piece of cardboard above her head.  The message is strange. It is written with a Sharpie pen. Burma, also called Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia. It is ruled by a mean group of soldiers. They got power in 1962. In 2007, people went into the street to protest. This was the first time in ten years that people had done this. The protests were led by monks. They wore yellow robes. People called the protests “The Saffron Revolution.”

At first, the government let the monks have peaceful meetings. But then things got violent. Some people say it was like a war between the monks and the soldiers. The soldiers attacked the monks’ homes. They took foreign reporters and put them in jail. A Japanese reporter named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007. He was just at a protest.

This is not new. Governments try to stop people from speaking out. They want to control everything.

Roman emperors said they were chosen by the gods. They ruled over everything. Japanese emperors are thought to be gods. They came to Earth to help people. Our president, George W. Bush, talks to a religious leader named Ted Haggard.

There are many examples of this. In 1989, people protested in Tiananmen Square. They wanted the Chinese government to change. Many people died. The government says 200-300 people died. But others say it was 2,000-3,000.

Another example is the Rwandan genocide. Hutu soldiers killed many Tutsis. They also killed people who did not agree with the government. Hitler did the same thing to Jewish people.

Duke Ellington was a good jazz musician. He played for many years and made his orchestra very good. Ellington did not always play the piano in his songs. But, he was a great song writer. He made songs that showed off the music of each player in his band. He made songs where players could sing new parts and songs where the band played together in a special way. Ellington made the band sound good all the time. He made new and exciting music.

A book about music, called The Grove Music Dictionary, says Ellington used his voice like an instrument. This is shown in his song "Creole Love Call". In this song, Ellington used voice to make the music sound different. He also made sure his singers fit the style of his other players.  "Creole Love Call" is a slow song. It has six parts:
Part 1: A voice and wind instruments talk back and forth. The voice starts smooth and then gets rougher.
Part 2: A trumpet player plays a solo. His music is soft and has sad sounds.
Part 3: A clarinet player plays a high, fast solo. The piano plays a soft beat underneath.
Part 4:  All the instruments play together like they did in Part 1. 
Part 5: This part is the most exciting. The wind instruments talk back and forth high. The brass and drums play in a special way.
Part 6: This part is like Part 1. The voice and wind instruments talk back and forth. This time the voice sounds rough.
At the end, there is a short part with a voice solo and a trombone playing a strange note.
Ellington used voice to make his music sound different. He did this a lot in his songs.

In another song called "Hot and Bothered," Ellington combined his ability to make songs sound good together with his love for different sounds. A trumpet player named "Bubber" Miley talks back and forth with a singer named Baby Cox. Their voices and music blend together.  In "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)," Ellington used a trombone player named Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton to start the song.

She always felt like she needed some thing. This want did not go away. It started when she was about fourteen, a young teenager. It was still there three years later. Now, she wanted a person, not a thing. But, she did not like any boys. Some boys liked her. They tried to ask her out, but no one was right for her. She asked herself why this was. She tried to think of a reason. She thought about it for years, but she could not find a good answer. So, she lived her life, always wondering about her wants.

One day at home was usually quiet. Her parents were good and calm. They never fought. They also seldom fought with her. The only time they fought was when she wanted to be more independent. She was the daughter of calm people, but she was very fun and outgoing. People liked her because she was nice.

Today was not a quiet day. She walked around her house, looking for something to do. Then, she heard a scream from the kitchen. It was her mother's voice. She ran to the kitchen. She was worried. "Mom! Mom, what is wrong?" Her mother was on the floor. She was in pain. She said, "Ouch" over and over. Her daughter ran to her and touched her. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to the hospital." Her mother spoke quickly. Her daughter knew she was in a lot of pain. "Okay, Mom. Where do you want me to pick you up?" Her mother pointed. The daughter was glad she had taken classes to get strong. She carried her mother to the car, put her in the back, and drove to the hospital.

The hospital smelled like medicine and sickness. It was scary, but she was too busy helping her mother to be afraid. She carried her mother in and asked for help. Some doctors came quickly. They put her mother on a bed and took her away. The daughter sat and waited, worried.

Her mother had fallen off a stool while she tried to get a vase from a high shelf.

This study looked at if eating a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) helps women stay healthy. The Med diet is good for you because it has lots of plants, like fruits, nuts, and beans. It also has healthy fats and fish.  It has less meat and unhealthy fats. 

Scientists wanted to see if this diet helps women avoid heart problems and strokes.  They looked at 74,886 women for 20 years.  

The women told the scientists what they ate. The scientists used this information to see how well each woman followed the Med diet.

The women who ate more like the Med diet had less heart problems and strokes.  This means that the Med diet can help women stay healthy.

In two thousand seven, America had a big money problem. Many people lost their jobs.  Homes lost value. Big companies had big trouble. This problem is still with us today. We must ask: how did this happen? How can we stop it? The money problem was made by bad choices by people who make laws. They pushed banks to give out bad loans to people who could not pay them back. The system to handle money was not strong enough. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac took these bad loans and made new packages of them. When people could not pay back the loans, the banks had no money. They put the problem onto the new packages and onto the whole country.
This problem started in nineteen ninety-nine when President Clinton wanted to be very popular. He wanted to stay in office.  So, he made it easier to give out loans. This made the bad loan problem worse later. A reporter for the New York Times said that giving out too many loans would be bad. He said that the government would have to help like they did with banks in the 1980s.
Many things made the problem worse. New kinds of loans were made. These loans were hard to understand. People took out too many loans. They put too much money into homes. When home prices went down, the banks lost money. 
The banks that bought the bad loans lost a lot of money. Five big banks had loans for four trillion dollars. This was a big part of the American economy. Some banks had to be sold for cheap. Others went out of business. Fannie and Freddie needed help from the government.

Ah, exposition. This is the part in your story where you show your writing skills. You can make your readers excited, or they might get bored and stop reading.  Dr. Merlin knows this problem well. She gets tired of long passages with no action or too much information.  Exposition is like a voice in your head that tells you to give all the backstory before the story even starts. This can be boring for readers.

"Show, don't tell" is important. But Dr. Merlin still writes long passages where nothing happens. Exposition is like a little voice that says, 'Tell the reader everything that happened.' In movies, this happens when one character tells another a lot of information, like in a long story. In books, the author does the telling.


Here is an example.  Imagine reading a story where the heroine met her husband at a party. They got married in a big ceremony, and then he was murdered in front of her.  You wouldn't want to read two pages about this, with only a few words from the characters.

Instead, the author should show you how much the husband loved his wife through his words and actions. You should also see how much his presence meant to her and how he changed her life.  If the story says she was deeply affected by his death, you should see that in her actions and thoughts.


You need more than just the basic facts of the story. You need to feel something. That's what makes a story exciting.

Sometimes it is tempting to skip over important details. Maybe you're introducing a new character who used to be in the Air Force. He now works the night shift at a gas station. He's been married twice, has no children, likes to fish on weekends, and wants to own the gas station someday.  He had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I saw two news shows from Columbus, Ohio. The first show was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). It was a live show. The first story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio. He hurt his wife. They did not say her name but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his picture. He looked bad. They talked about this story for two minutes. They said he hurt his wife many times. Police took him to jail.

The next story was about a man named Travis Buyers. He was 18 years old. Someone shot him in Sharon Woods. He was hurt very badly. No one was caught. The police were looking for the person who did it. This story was short. I think this was because the man was black. I have seen this before. The news does not talk much about crimes against black people. If a white person is hurt, the news talks about it a lot.

The next story was about a helicopter. Someone shot at it. A small bullet hit the helicopter. The police want to find the person who did it. They are offering five thousand dollars for information.

Next, they talked about the weather. It would rain on Saturday. It would be hot.

They also talked about a robbery. A man robbed a store. He was black. He wore a sweatshirt. He was tall and skinny. I think they talked too much about his race.

They talked about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was in jail. He sold drugs. He was from Texas. He was sentenced to 300 months in jail. I don't know why they said that instead of 25 years. They also said he was Hispanic. I don't think this was important to the story.

Brothers have a strong bond. This bond has many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and meanness. Brothers know each other better than anyone else. They see themselves when they look at their brother.

The real nature of this bond shows when things are bad. This bond can be good or bad. These feelings are strong. It is hard to understand these feelings.

One way to understand is to see the results of these feelings. When a brother looks at another brother, he sees his own self. He sees himself as he really is. His actions and the results show who he is.

In the story "The Scarlet Ibis", two brothers show this theme. They go on a trip in a beautiful place. They have a hard time. Pride and sadness meet at the end. Only one brother lives. The story shows these feelings through the main character, Doodle. It also shows the main character's feelings about the world.

The main character feels pride. From the time he and Doodle, his little brother, first go out, to the end, he feels bad about Doodle. He wanted a brother who could learn things. He wanted someone to race and play with. He wanted someone who could do all the things he liked to do.

Doodle was very weak. He could not run or jump. This made the main character sad. He even thought about hurting Doodle. But then Doodle smiled at him. The main character felt better. He loved Doodle.

The human brain is very hard to understand. People use many words to talk about how it works.

At first, they said the brain was like a wax tablet. Later they said it was like paper, then a book. Now they say it is like a computer.  But these words are not perfect.

We learn about the brain by looking at how it works. Our senses send information to the brain. The brain turns this information into electrical signals. It uses these signals to understand the world.

When we see something, the brain puts together small pieces of information like color and shape to make a whole picture. This is called bottom-up processing. The brain also uses what it already knows to help understand new information. This is called top-down processing.

The brain has a filter that decides what is important. It pays attention to important things and ignores less important things.

The brain stores information in different ways. Sensory memory is very short, only lasting a few seconds. Working memory holds information for a little longer, about 20 seconds. Long-term memory stores information for a long time.

There are many ways to understand how the brain stores knowledge. Some ideas come from watching people remember things. Other ideas come from computers. Some ideas come from studying the brain itself.

One idea is that knowledge is stored in a network. Each idea is like a node in a network. Ideas that are related to each other are connected.

Aldous Huxley looks at the danger of new technology and how money makes it worse. He writes about this in his book, *Brave New World*.  People in this book like their groups more than themselves. They are taught to be happy all the time. The people are like toys in a game. The World Controller tells them what to think. If you look at the book with a special way of looking called Marxist theism, you can see that Huxley does not like these things.  

Huxley uses words like "same" and "thing" to show how bad capitalism is. He says that most people don't know how money really works. They just want more things. This is because the people in charge control what they think.  The poor people in *Brave New World* are like workers who don't know they are being taken advantage of.  They are told to sleep a lot so they will want to buy more things. The World Controller makes them do this.  The rich people know what is happening, but they do nothing.

In *Brave New World*, people don't have real relationships. They are all the same. Maybe Huxley is saying that technology and money stop people from being free. People don't love each other. They only think about how they look. The different groups in this book are happy with their place in society. This shows how capitalism makes people obey.

I am a student at University Park. I have been here for two and a half years. I live in a dorm. Many students, like me, have trouble getting around campus.

My first year, I lived in a dorm far from most buildings. Going to classes in the center of campus took a long time. I spoke with a former student. He said the dorms used to be far from the rest of the school. Now, the space is full of new buildings and sports fields.

As the campus grows, getting around gets harder. What is the best way to get around? A bicycle is good. But students need to ride them, and the school needs to be built for bikes.

My friend said bikes are good.  He said they are the best way to travel.  You can go far on a bike with little food. Many students live off campus, like me. I live just as far from the center as some dorms.

I bought a bike this year. My house is far from my classes. It takes 25 minutes to walk. But on a bike, it takes 5 minutes.

The problem is, the road to my classes is not good for bikes.  Walking is good too, but I am too busy.

If I did not have a bike, I would have to walk. That would take a lot of time. I do not have that time.
